definition.value: A lysophosphatidylcholine 22:6 in which the acyl group is specified as (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoyl and is located at position 2.
A 1-O-acyl-N-acylsphingosine in which the N- and O-acyl groups are specified as acetyl and linoleoyl respectively.
A 1-O-acyl-N-acylsphingosine in which the N- and O-acyl groups are specified as acetyl and (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoyl respectively.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of 2-oleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine; major species at pH 7.3.
An O-acyl carbohydrate that is beta-D-glucose bearing a trans-4-coumaroyl substituent at position 6.

A limonoid with formula C28H34O9. It is commonly found in edible citrus fruits including lemons, limes, oranges, and grapefruits. The compound exhibits a variety of biological and pharmacological activities including anticancer, antiinflammatory, antiobesity, and antiviral.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of 2-linoleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine; major species at pH 7.3.

A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of 2-arachidonoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine; major species at pH 7.3.
An O-acyl carbohydrate that is alpha-D-glucose bearing a trans-4-coumaroyl substituent at position 6.
An O-acyl carbohydrate that is beta-D-glucose bearing a cis-4-coumaroyl substituent at position 3.
An O-acyl carbohydrate that is beta-D-glucose bearing a trans-4-coumaroyl substituent at position 4.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of trans-coumaric acid with one of the hydroxy groups of meso-tartaric acid.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of cis-coumaric acid with one of the hydroxy groups of meso-tartaric acid.
A glycophytoceramide having a 6-O-[(4-chlorophenyl)carbamoyl]-alpha-D-galactopyranosyl residue at the O-1 position and an hexacosanoyl group attached to the nitrogen.
A galactosylceramide sulfate in which the sulfo group is located at position 3 and the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as docosanoyl.
A ribose derivative that is the 5-phospho derivative of phenyl alpha-D-ribofuranoside.
An enal that is (2E,6Z)-nona-2,6-diene substituted by an oxo group at position 1.
A glycophytoceramide having a 6-O-(4-pyridylcarbamoyl)-alpha-D-galactopyranosyl residue at the O-1 position and an hexacosanoyl group attached to the nitrogen.
The (S)-enantiomer of laudanine
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of laudanine, obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group.
A benzyltetrahydroisoquinoline that is norlaudanosoline carrying four methyl substituents at positions N-1, O-6, O-7 and O-4'.
An organic anion obtained by selective deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group of kaempferol 3-O-beta-D-galactoside; major species at pH 7.3.
The (R)-enantiomer of laudanine
A racemate composed of equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-laudanosoline
Any isotopically modified compound that has one or more hydrogen atoms replaced by deuterium.
A glycophytoceramide having a 6-O-(1-naphthylcarbamoyl)-alpha-D-galactopyranosyl residue at the O-1 position and a hexacosanoyl group attached to the nitrogen.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by deprotonation of the free phosphate OH groups of O-(alpha-D-glucosyl) poly(glycerol phosphate)
A fatty alcohol that is  nonacosane substituted by a hydroxy group at position 10.
An AMP-sugar in which the 2'-hydroxy group of AMP carries a 5-phospho-beta-D-ribosyl substituent. Monomer unit of poly(ADP-Rib) [poly(adenosine diphosphate ribose)].

An AMP-sugar in which the 2'-hydroxy group of AMP carries a 5-phospho-beta-D-ribosyl substituent, the 2-hydroxy group of which itself carries a further 5-phospho-beta-D-ribosyl substituent. Branched portion of poly(ADP-Rib) [poly(adenosine diphosphate ribose)].
A single-stranded DNA oligonucleotide comprised of four deoxyadenosine and three thymidine residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence AATTTAA.
A single-stranded DNA oligonucleotide comprised of four deoxyadenosine, two thymidine residues and one deoxycytidine residue connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence AATTCAA.

A monocarboxylic acid that is propionic acid substituted at position 2 by a 2-(4-chlorophenyl)-1,3-benzoxazol-5-yl group. It was used as a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug until 1982 when it was withdrawn from the market due to adverse side-effects including liver necrosis, photosensitivity, and carcinogenicity in animals.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of cis-ferulic acid with one of the hydroxy groups of L-tartaric acid.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of trans-ferulic acid with one of the hydroxy groups of L-tartaric acid.
A ferulic acid consisting of cis-cinnamic acid bearing methoxy and hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 4 respectively on the phenyl ring.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of cis-ferulic acid with one of the hydroxy groups of D-tartaric acid.

A carbohydrazide obtained by formal condensation of one of the carboxy groups from butylmalonic acid with the hydrazino group of 1,2-diphenylhydrazine. Used (as its calcium semihydrate) for treatment of rheumatoid arthritis.
A dialkyl ketone that is  nonacosane substituted by an oxo group at position 10.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of trans-ferulic acid with one of the hydroxy groups of D-tartaric acid.
A L-tryptophan derivative that is L-tryptophan in which the hydrogen attached to the indole nitrogen replaced by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
A hydrate that is the hemihydrate form of bumadizone calcium. Used for treatment of rheumatoid arthritis.
An organic calcium salt having 2-[(1,2-diphenylhydrazino)carbonyl]hexanoate as the counterion. Used (as its hemihydrate) for treatment of rheumatoid arthritis.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of bumadizone, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A catechin that is flavan carrying five hydroxy substituents at positions 3, 3', 4', 5 and 7 (the 2S,3S-stereoisomer).
A gallate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of gallic acid with the (3S)-hydroxy group of (+)-epicatechin.

An imidazole substituted at positions 1, 4 and 5 by 4-aminosulfonylphenyl, chloro and 3-fluoro-4-methyoxyphenyl groups respectively. A selective cyclooxygenase 2 inhibitor, it is used in veterinary medicine for the control of pain and inflammation associated with osteoarthritis in dogs.

A monocarboxylic acid that is (S)-hydratropic acid substituted at position 3 on the phenyl ring by a benzoyl group. A cyclooxygenase inhibitor, it is used to relieve short-term pain, such as muscular pain, dental pain and dysmenorrhoea.

A linear tetrasaccharide glycosyl group comprising, in a (1->4), (1->4), (1->3) sequence, a 4-deoxy-4-formamido-beta-D-quinovose group and two 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-alpha-D-galacturonamidyl residues linked to a 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-beta-D-quinovose residue at the reducing end.
A straight-chain alkane comprising of 29 carbon atoms.
